'''Rubén Estephan Vargas Martínez ''' (born 5 August 1998) is a Swiss professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Winger|winger]] or [[attacking midfielder]] for Spanish {{Spanish football updater|Sevilla}} club [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] and the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]].

==Club career==
Vargas made his professional debut for [[FC Luzern]] in a 1–1 tie with [[FC Zürich]] on 27 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sfl.ch/superleague/matchcenter/match/201718/luz-fcz-13019/ | title=LUZ - FCZ &#124; Super League 2017/2018 &#124; Match }}</ref>

He signed a 5 year contract with [[FC Augsburg|Augsburg]] in the summer of 2019,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://fcaugsburg.de/wns/ruben-vargas-joins-fc-augsburg/?lang=en|title=Ruben Vargas joins FC Augsburg|date=18 June 2019|website=FC Augsburg|language=en-US|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> becoming the first Bundesliga player of Dominican descent. He scored his first goal in his second match, against [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/who-is-ruben-vargas-augsburg-shaqiri-lichsteiner-protege-7076|title=Ruben Vargas: Lichtsteiner's protege, the Bundesliga's top-scoring new player and Augsburg's answer to Shaqiri|website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website|language=en|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>

On 9 January 2025, Vargas signed a contract with Spanish club [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] until 2029.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sevilla FC|url=https://sevillafc.es/en/current/news/signing-ruben-vargas-2025|title=RUBÉN VARGAS BECOMES FIRST SIGNING OF 2025|date=9 January 2025|access-date=10 January 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
Vargas made his [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland senior team]] debut on 8 September 2019, in a [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group D|UEFA Euro 2020 qualifier]] against [[Gibraltar national football team|Gibraltar]]. He replaced [[Granit Xhaka]] in the 74th minute.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[UEFA]]|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/match/2026193--switzerland-vs-gibraltar/|title=Switzerland v Gibraltar game report|date=8 September 2019}}</ref> On 18 November, he scored his first senior international goal against the same opposition in a 6–1 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.rts.ch/sport/video/football/10876135-grd-gibraltar-suisse-16-la-reaction-de-vargas-apres-la-victoire.html|title= Gr.D, Gibraltar - Suisse (1-6): La réaction de Vargas après la victoire |language=French|date=18 November 2024|access-date=16 June 2024|website=RTS}}</ref>

Vargas scored a crucial penalty for Switzerland during [[UEFA Euro 2020]] in a shootout against [[France national football team|France]] on 28 June in the [[UEFA Euro 2020#Round of 16|round of 16]], helping Switzerland qualify for the quarter-final.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2021/jun/28/france-v-switzerland-euro-2020-last-16-score-updates-live|title=France 3-3 Switzerland (Aet; pens 4-5): Euro 2020 last 16 – as it happened|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 June 2021|last1=Murray|first1=Scott}}</ref> However, Vargas, later missed a penalty for Switzerland during the shootout against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] on 2 July in the quarter-final, which they would end up losing.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[UEFA]]|url= https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/2024485--switzerland-vs-spain/|title=Switzerland v Spain game report|date=2 July 2021}}{{dead link|date=March 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

Vargas started all four of Switzerland's matches at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], assisting [[Remo Freuler]]'s winning goal in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] decider against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] on 2 December.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63752146|title=World Cup 2022: Serbia 2-3 Switzerland - Swiss through after exciting victory|date=1 December 2022|access-date=16 June 2024|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, Vargas was named in Switzerland's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/switzerland-announce-26-man-squad-euro-2024-2024-06-07/|title=Switzerland announce 26-man squad for Euro 2024|date=7 June 2024|website=Reuters|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref> He started the team's opening match, playing 74 minutes of a 3–1 win over [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] in Cologne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy99107knekt#Line-ups|title=Hungary 1-3 Switzerland LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 - score, updates & reaction|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref> He was awarded [[player of the match]] for Switzerland's [[UEFA Euro 2024#Round of 16|round of 16]] game against defending champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]], both scoring and assisting a goal in a 2–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b3feb119740-4173d9eff275-1000--switzerland-2-0-italy-swiss-club-together-in-berlin/|title=Switzerland 2–0 Italy: Swiss club together in Berlin|website=[[UEFA]]|publisher=Union of European Football Associations|date=29 June 2024|access-date=29 June 2024}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Vargas was born in [[Adligenswil]], Switzerland, to a [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominican]] father called Victor Vargas alias "Filete", and a [[Swiss people|Swiss]] mother, and holds citizenship of both nations.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.luzernerzeitung.ch/sport/fussball/fcl/vargas-ich-will-einen-stammplatz;art9653,1182028|title=FCL-Talent Ruben Vargas: "Ich will einen Stammplatz"|newspaper=[[Luzerner Zeitung]] |first=Daniel |last=Wyrsch |date=2018-01-15 |access-date=2026-04-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212000340/http://www.luzernerzeitung.ch/sport/fussball/fcl/vargas-ich-will-einen-stammplatz;art9653,1182028|archive-date=2018-02-12 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

